  ('best_practice', 'Hero anatomy that converts — copy-first ''typeframe'', kicker/headline/description/CTA, and a human whose gaze points to the CTA', 'A converting hero is built copy-first as a "typeframe" — a low-fidelity wireframe with high-fidelity text — so the message, hierarchy, and spacing are nailed before any pixels of imagery exist; designing words to fit a chosen background image is the backwards process that produces beautiful-but-empty heroes. The proven element stack is: a kicker (social proof, e.g. client numbers), a brief crystal-clear headline that names the visitor''s problem/solution, a description that pre-empts 1–2 common objections, and one primary CTA (add a secondary CTA only for high-ticket/high-friction offers). For imagery, ~99% of businesses convert better with a real human than with abstract or AI-generated backgrounds, because people let the viewer imagine themselves in the situation — and the human''s gaze should point toward the CTA, not at the camera. Reinforce with guiding lines (break text to create diagonal flow toward the button) and subtly color-matching one element of the photo to the CTA color. Heroes fail when aesthetics are decoupled from the message: mysterious copy, generic stock photos, and multiple competing CTAs. (Pairs with [hero_simplicity_prototypicality], [section_visual_cues_direct_to_cta].)', '{"applicable_when":"hero_main — composing the message and imagery of an above-the-fold hero","category":"hero_layout","evidence_source":"Hype4 Academy ''Hero Sections That Really Convert'' (hype4.academy/articles/design/hero-sections-that-really-convert)"}'::jsonb, '[-0.018403709,0.0089740185,0.01219343,-0.08475611,-0.010071887,-0.00981989,-0.003189064,0.01120966,-0.0004148059,-0.013047965,-0.021933295,0.012593513,0.008929083,0.0014219476,0.14572538,0.0039393944,0.004192967,0.010541388,0.003635365,0.0054443073,-0.0022490504,0.00537695,-0.023634823,0.0014737874,-0.011714202,-0.009230634,0.0073300297,0.013297393,0.036441263,