  ('best_practice', 'Hero composition — headline as anchor, generous vertical rhythm, text-over-image contrast, one dominant CTA', 'Build the hero on a clear visual flow: headline → subhead → single primary CTA, with the headline as the bold, high-contrast anchor surrounded by whitespace so it dominates. Use a consistent vertical rhythm — roughly 24–40px between headline, supporting line, and CTA — and keep margin around the whole block so it breathes. When copy sits over a photo, video, or gradient, guarantee readability with a scrim or sufficient contrast; low contrast makes even a beautiful hero unusable. Choose exactly one primary CTA and let secondary actions read as clearly lower-emphasis. On mobile, collapse to a single column and reorder so it stacks headline → image → CTA (never image-first), and scale type responsively — a 72px desktop headline becomes ~36–42px on mobile without losing its weight. The hero''s type scale also sets the ceiling for the rest of the page: H2s below must read as clearly secondary to the hero headline.', '{"applicable_when":"hero_main layout and type sizing, desktop and mobile","category":"hero_layout","evidence_source":"Flux Academy ''How To Design A Great Hero Section'' (youtube.com/watch?v=0h68pEOn_Rk; flux-academy.com/resources/design-the-perfect-hero-section)"}'::jsonb, '[-0.0038392537,0.015060152,0.00792482,-0.090150036,-0.015453541,-0.0053139804,-0.027535897,-0.008557936,0.0071439627,-0.016852235,-0.022041721,0.015509657,-0.018037397,0.004093712,0.1291999,-0.0024347585,-0.026839506,-0.016255582,0.004923519,0.007663936,0.010498263,-0.0077297417,-0.016702903,-0.0022401118,-0.01129716,-0.018564854,0.04774727,0.008938004,0.026179658,0.030945856,-0.011335099,-0.008278829,0.038365245,0.0067355684,-0.0151963625,0.033205908,0.005586162,-0.025299637,0.008898321,0.029787226,0.0047664004,0.0031860457,0.015212367,0.0023307665,-0.014754155,-0.022940945,-0.007077091,-0.009946527,0.01706023,0.04279891,-0.029519089,0.012015277,-0.02555074