  ('best_practice', 'Integrate mid-page section banners with whitespace — loud color-block backgrounds make them look like ads', 'The myth that an intermediate section banner needs a loud, garish background to get noticed is backwards: a strident isolated color block is exactly the silhouette users have learned to read as advertising, so it gets dodged (banner blindness). Malewicz''s layout teardowns show modern section banners integrating organically into the page using whitespace, restrained color, and shared typography — the banner feels like a continuation of the content, not a billboard dropped on top of it. Use generous padding and alignment to the page grid rather than a contrasting full-bleed color to set the section apart; let hierarchy and spacing do the separating. This keeps mid-page banners (testimonials, secondary offers, traffic redirects) feeling editorial and trustworthy while still standing as distinct sections.', '{"applicable_when":"section banners that divide Home/landing sections (testimonials, promos, traffic redirects)","category":"hierarchy","evidence_source":"Michal Malewicz / Hype4 Academy — UI layout teardowns on section design (youtube.com/@MichalMalewicz); reinforced by NN/g banner blindness"}'::jsonb, '[-0.0027207697,0.011203576,-0.004190613,-0.09076949,-0.0064856973,-0.0010638195,0.007254745,-0.016721027,-0.0014848303,-0.020582559,0.004845485,0.010256668,-0.0022050664,-0.0071383463,0.11242291,0.008895254,0.018994983,-0.005487028,0.0036797402,-0.011111055,0.032479625,-0.008076354,-0.0035107187,-0.011010107,0.0071073114,-0.03113342,-0.009230922,0.010490653,0.022266543,0.013069325,-0.020256812,0.028315749,0.05042734,0.0191854,0.006224031,0.03409044,0.012523399,0.009342471,0.0056233606,0.028551945,-0.007042757,0.006980665,0.0075219786,-0.016016928,-0.008336451,-0.02304694,0.004089275,-0.014952532,-0.010639474,0.03541262,-0.0057829046,0.020619081,-0.013611152,-0.16121115,-0.0051333276,0.0026840137,-0.0008821293,0.0040038084,0.010973146,0.0