  ('best_practice', 'Keep hero banners visually simple and prototypical — familiar layouts convert better than ultra-creative ones', 'Users form a stable aesthetic and trust judgment of a page in roughly 50 milliseconds, and that snap judgment is driven by two measurable traits: low visual complexity and high prototypicality. Visually complex heroes are consistently rated as less appealing and less trustworthy, while "prototypical" layouts — ones that look the way visitors expect a storefront hero to look — score highest because they cost the brain almost no processing effort. The implication for banner generation: prefer a single dominant headline, one clear CTA, and a conventional left-copy / right-image (or centered) arrangement over novel, ultra-creative compositions. Creativity should live in the imagery and copy, not in a layout that forces the user to relearn where to look. High cognitive load at the hero is a direct conversion tax — every extra element competing for attention lowers the odds the user grasps the value proposition in under 5 seconds.', '{"applicable_when":"all hero_main banners — the first above-the-fold impression","category":"hero_layout","evidence_source":"CXL ''Why Simple Website Design is The Best'' (cxl.com/blog/why-simple-websites-are-scientifically-better); Reinecke & Gajos 2014 ''visual complexity & prototypicality''; Google 2012 visual-complexity study; Lindgaard 2006 (50ms first impression)"}'::jsonb, '[-0.023397243,0.0088749435,0.010613165,-0.079842456,-0.007851535,0.0086646145,-0.007100273,0.0043183137,0.00896785,-0.017857958,-0.012392764,-0.008401846,0.014449279,-0.008439484,0.13312654,0.01892479,-0.019071499,-0.026659641,0.004001647,-0.008277403,0.0046238527,0.010549089,-0.029797267,0.002827813,-0.01090947,-0.014901896,-7.763469e-05,0.00826601,0.029274903,0.02474467,-0.006484696,0.018126244,0.021361798,0.006457227,0.009869423,0.025024867,0.01091714,-0.033261478,0.0013144067,0.03170129,0.008857035,-0.030239552,0.012898535,0.00885