  ('best_practice', 'Make the hero look like content, not an ad — ad-styled heroes trigger banner blindness', 'Banner blindness is selective attention: users instinctively skip page regions they perceive — correctly or not — as advertising, and NN/g eye-tracking heatmaps show fixations on ad-like blocks can be a tiny fraction of what their size warrants (in one case ~33× smaller than expected). Three signals trigger this avoidance: ad-typical placement (top strip, right rail), ad-like visual treatment (heavy animation, fancy framing, loud isolated color blocks), and proximity to real ads. A hero that adopts these traits gets dodged even though it is the brand''s own primary message. Design the hero to read as page content: integrate it with the page''s type and color system, lead with a genuine value proposition rather than a promotional shout, and avoid the bordered-box-on-colored-background "this is an ad" silhouette. The goal is for the user''s eye to treat the hero as the thing they came for, not as something to scroll past.', '{"applicable_when":"all hero_main and top-of-page banners","category":"hero_layout","evidence_source":"Nielsen Norman Group ''Banner Blindness Revisited: Users Dodge Ads on Mobile and Desktop'' (nngroup.com/articles/banner-blindness-old-and-new-findings) — eye-tracking heatmaps"}'::jsonb, '[-0.020754527,0.013754557,0.015791455,-0.08038645,-0.018093724,0.00055537745,-0.004497758,0.0053743147,-0.013077127,-0.04075431,-0.024243925,0.008629928,-0.003918323,0.0040796795,0.1252651,0.0047400785,0.0015751107,-0.010267372,-0.007074446,0.010317479,0.0029387278,-0.012634015,-0.011753339,0.020936446,-0.019809525,-0.014095704,0.017026665,-0.004415294,0.03189781,0.022049544,-0.011445,0.020068416,0.042975895,0.017366264,0.013748295,0.020023761,0.018513326,-0.012269504,0.023783596,0.015254193,0.02051862,-0.002001838,0.019993538,0.008457018,-0.028769365,-0.006146499,0.022249777,-0.011130493,0.007579669,0.036963534,-0.031014653,0.023140814,-0.0109307775,-0