  ('best_practice', 'Miller''s Law — reduce on-screen complexity and chunk content; every extra element raises error and abandonment', 'Miller''s Law is popularly cited as 7±2 items of working memory, but the practical lesson is broader: "the more elements people have to process, the easier for them to make a mistake," and a busier screen raises the chance of error or outright abandonment. Treat the magic number as a reminder to reduce overall complexity, not a hard quota. For banners this means limiting each banner to one core message with minimal supporting elements, and for multi-step flows (e.g. configurators, lead forms behind a CTA) splitting the task into easy, logical steps instead of presenting everything at once. Chunk feature lists, trust cues, and benefits into small grouped units rather than one dense block. (Pairs with [hero_simplicity_prototypicality], [hierarchy_supporting_copy_max_two_lines], [pdp_feature_callout_persuasion].)', '{"applicable_when":"deciding how much information and how many elements to place in a banner or section","category":"ux_law","evidence_source":"Hype4 Academy / SquarePlanet — Laws of UX: Miller''s Law (hype4.academy/learn/laws-of-ux/millers-law-in-ux)"}'::jsonb, '[0.0057381517,0.002533123,0.02114658,-0.052957986,0.0103516895,-0.021506447,0.029015,0.0013365758,0.021426335,0.008176613,-0.04018337,-0.02569769,0.012363573,-0.020552518,0.12885451,0.040843688,0.0069590686,-0.007628932,0.00062616746,0.003524855,-0.00511893,0.02789111,-0.03705911,-0.0100685125,-0.0020736807,-0.008222882,0.009128482,0.0076654293,0.045617316,0.004370604,0.008966371,0.029261447,0.024302956,-0.014496273,-0.0013800116,0.005188587,0.03163407,-0.007945176,-0.005109304,0.027836453,0.009993496,-0.0010440785,0.012704255,-0.0072575863,-0.018379606,-0.002547099,0.010490611,-0.017415889,0.007506349,0.046114005,-0.010282083,0.021244626,-0.009955169,-0.16663352,0.007009984,0.0023701123,0.012953151,-0.0046204613,0.026135666,0.0010804741,0.015393625,-0.00045803026,