  ('best_practice', 'On category pages, never let a hero banner push subcategory navigation below the fold', 'Baymard identifies leading a category page with a hero banner that pushes subcategory navigation below the fold as "the single most common and most damaging mistake" on intermediary category pages — when the first screen is all promotion, a significant share of users never reach the navigation that would actually move them toward products. Promotional and editorial banners have a legitimate place on category pages, but only on desktop and only after subcategory navigation in visual priority. The category banner must not compete with or bury the catalog and nav: subcategory tiles should be the prominent above-the-fold content, with the promo banner as a supporting, secondary element. For the banner agent this means category-header banners should be sized as headers, not full-viewport heroes, and should sit alongside or beneath navigation rather than displacing it.', '{"applicable_when":"category and collection header banners on intermediary listing pages","category":"catalog","evidence_source":"Baymard Institute ''Ecommerce Category Pages: Definition, Usage & Design Tips'' (baymard.com/learn/ecommerce-category-page)"}'::jsonb, '[-0.019613355,0.010503007,-0.0030565828,-0.08759163,-0.01590576,0.02217878,-0.032248143,-0.00335145,-0.0093721,-0.015964977,-0.02964979,0.005748005,0.025085038,-0.011849909,0.102841824,0.023010237,0.024491819,-0.002290284,-4.3249493e-05,-0.017515149,0.015614895,0.004327917,-0.010196829,-0.0044334815,0.0009903649,-0.006666293,-0.013649122,0.012599877,0.036170132,0.007181676,-0.009464357,0.009905301,0.036442354,-0.008329087,0.0011837545,0.0062368023,0.003071987,-0.028739855,0.0070559043,0.023545228,-0.0004589627,0.016774286,0.010686312,0.0115334485,-0.009661179,-0.011569104,0.010948792,-0.018546179,-0.012107813,0.036863748,-0.03335053,0.0230563,-0.013477869,-0.16873072,0.0053014997,0.0050142817,0.0033927513,-0.017108256,-0.011832836,-0.0