67,0.00886593,0.008543933,0.027744556,0.0067658285,0.009796546,0.01478457,-0.0077945697,0.0074403263,0.009722487,-0.034229826,-0.021316728,0.0006271388,-0.022344774,0.008335434,0.008674894,0.00778638,0.00291856,0.022678267,0.0063618207,-0.007948286,-0.002480341,0.0059913523,0.050729368,-0.0003816866,-0.0018025402,-0.023897354,-0.017362967,-0.017037682,-0.011772285,0.0058312076,0.015021453,-0.006097516,0.003381685,0.0058269985,0.030539615,-0.023774723,-0.00095320126,0.012865517,-0.0077438173,-0.0048774364,-0.017402353,-0.016928481,-0.0022427216,-0.02272125,0.016114589,-0.019884566,-0.0016375828,-0.008025825,-0.008164982,-0.0013202919,0.029001651,0.02203489]'::vector, null),
  ('best_practice', 'Use directional visual cues — arrows, gaze direction, encapsulation — to steer the eye to the section CTA', 'Visual cues literally point the visitor at the element you want them to act on. CXL''s eye-tracking study built identical landing pages differing only in cue: an explicit hand-drawn arrow pointing at the form produced the longest time on page and concentrated attention on the form, while a photo of a person looking *away* from the form drew the least attention and interaction. Two cue families work together — explicit cues (arrows, lines) spread attention across the whole pointed-at region and are strongest for grabbing it, while a person''s eye-gaze cue directs attention precisely to the spot being looked at. So in a section banner with a human subject, orient their gaze toward the headline or CTA, never out of frame. Reinforce with implicit cues: encapsulation (a frame/container around the CTA), color contrast, and whitespace that isolates the button. The takeaway for the banner agent: every section banner should contain at least one cue aimed at its single CTA, and any person depicted must look toward — not away from — the action.', '{"applicable_when":"mid-page section banners and any banner whose goal is a single click","category":"conversion","evidence_source":"CXL ''Visual Cues in Digital Marketing'' (cxl.com/blog/visual-cues) and CXL original visual-cue eye-tracking study (cxl.com/research-study/visual-cue-study)"}'::jsonb, '[-0.036429897,-0.0011994087,-0.005737203,-0.08592334,-0.017543044,-0.00014854968,-0.009331011,-0.0034263122,-0.021154363,-0.0040879305,-0.0001612784,0.0044016857,-0.010208711,-0.0021560527,0.14437988,0.0039122705,0.0056747724,-0.010415974,2.5276455e-05,-0.011652498,0.0034911796,0.0046884636,-0.029687647,-0.005692608,0.003155982,-0.020156648,-0.004857239,0.001853145,0.04170453,0.01664723,-0.024634626,0.01566392,0.02452076,0.022344925,0.019724844,0.017943608,0.0020623293,-0.012562259,0.042945612,0.0075803576,0.0